HEADWORD: Bestiary
<hw>Bes"ti*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>bestiarium</ets>, fr. L. <ets>bestiarius</ets> pert. to beasts, fr.
<ets>bestia</ets> beast: cf. F. <ets>bestiaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>A
treatise on beasts; esp., one of the moralizing or allegorical beast
tales written in the Middle Ages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>bestiary</qex> . . . in itself one of the numerous
medi⟦ae⟧val renderings of the fantastic mystical Zoology.</q>
<rj><qau>Saintsbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

